43: /**
44:  * Root of Type symbol hierarchy for values in the build language.
45:  *
46:  * <p>Type symbols are primarily used for their <code>convert</code> method, which is a kind of cast
47:  * operator enabling conversion from untyped (Object) references to values in the build language, to
48:  * typed references.
49:  *
50:  * <p>For example, this code type-converts a value <code>x</code> returned by the evaluator, to a
51:  * list of strings:
52:  *
53:  * <pre>
54:  *  Object x = expr.eval(env);
55:  *  List&lt;String&gt; s = Type.STRING_LIST.convert(x);
56:  *  </pre>
57:  *
58:  * <p><b>BEFORE YOU ADD A NEW TYPE:</b>
59:  *
60:  * <p>We frequently get requests to create a new kind of attribute type whenever a use case doesn't
61:  * seem to fit into one of the existing types. This is almost always a bad idea. The most complex
62:  * type we currently have is probably STRING_LIST_DICT or maybe LABEL_KEYED_STRING_DICT. But no
63:  * matter what you support, someone will always want to add another layer of structure. It's even
64:  * been suggested to allow JSON or arbitrary Starlark values in attributes.
65:  *
66:  * <p>Adding a new type has implications for many different systems. The whole of the loading phase
67:  * needs to know about the type -- how to serialize it, how to format it for `bazel query`, how to
68:  * traverse label dependencies embedded within it. Then you need to think about how to represent
69:  * attribute values of that type in Starlark within a rule implementation function, and come up with
70:  * a good name for that type in the Starlark `attr` module. All of the tooling for formatting,
71:  * linting, and analyzing BUILD files may need to be updated.
72:  *
73:  * <p>It's usually possible to accomplish the end goal without making the target attribute grammar
74:  * more expressive. If it's not, that may be a sign that attributes are not the right mechanism to
75:  * use, and perhaps instead you should use opaque string identifiers, or labels to sub-targets with
76:  * more structure (think toolchains, platforms, config_setting).
77:  *
78:  * <p>Any new attribute type should be general-purpose and meet a high bar of usefulness (unlikely
79:  * since we seem to be doing fine so far without it), and not overly complicate BUILD files or rule
80:  * implementation functions.
81:  */
82: // TODO(adonovan): update documentation here and elsewhere to use the term
83: // "rule attribute values" or "valid attribute types" where appropriate,
84: // and not "value in the build language", which is a much broader set of
85: // possible Starlark values. Also link to the canonical set of valid attribute
86: // types, both Starlark and native.
87: public abstract class Type<T> {
88: 
